Mexican Stocks: Coca-Cola Femsa, Elektra Advance; Bimbo Drops

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   J .   L e v i n
-- 
2011-04-27T14:55:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-27/mexican-stocks-coca-cola-femsa-elektra-advance-bimbo-drops.html
The following companies are having
unusual price changes in  Mexico  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 9:52 a.m. New York time.  The IPC index fell 0.1 percent to 36,843.00.  Airport operators: Mexico’s Communications and
Transportation Ministry received bids for the Riviera Maya
airport in southeast Mexico from a group comprised of Grupo
Mexico SAB and Grupo Aeroportuario del Pacifico SAB and a group
comprised of Tradeco Infrastructura SA and Corp. America SA, the
ministry said late yesterday in a statement. A group headed by
Grupo Aeroportuario del Sureste SAB presented a document asking
the government to consider its proposal if it successfully
appeals an antitrust ruling barring its participation.  Grupo Aeroportuario del Sureste (ASURB MM), the operator of
airports in southern Mexico, slid 1 percent to 66.50 pesos.
Grupo Aeroportuario del Pacifico (GAPB MM), the operator of
airports in the Pacific and central regions of Mexico, added 1
percent to 48.01 pesos.  Coca-Cola Femsa SAB (KOFL MM) advanced 0.6 percent to 92.85
pesos.  Latin America ’s largest soft-drink bottler said first-
quarter net income rose 6 percent to 2.2 billion pesos ($189.8
million), according to a statement to the stock exchange today.
Operating income increased 10 percent to 3.9 billion pesos.
First-quarter sales were 25.8 billion pesos.  Grupo Bimbo SAB (BIMBOA MM) tumbled 1.3 percent to 25.19
pesos. The world’s largest bread maker said first-quarter profit
fell 5.7 percent to 1.2 billion pesos, the company said in a
statement to the stock exchange yesterday. Operating income
slipped 9.8 percent to 2.4 billion pesos. Revenue was 29.3
billion pesos.  Grupo Elektra SA (ELEKTRA* MM) climbed 0.6 percent to
512.85 pesos. The retail and banking company controlled by
billionaire  Ricardo Salinas  said first-quarter net income surged
25 percent to 420.6 million pesos, according to a filing to
Mexico’s stock exchange yesterday. Operating income increased 16
percent to 1.4 billion pesos. Revenue was 12.6 billion pesos.  TV Azteca SAB (AZTECACP MM) surged 3 percent to 8.55 pesos.
Mexico’s second-largest broadcast television network said first-
quarter net income rose 23 percent to 162 million pesos,
according to a filing to Mexico’s stock exchange yesterday.
Operating income increased 3.4 percent to 653.7 million pesos.
Revenue totaled 2.3 billion pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan J. Levin in Mexico City at 
